The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Thursday, March 18, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		Twenty-two-year-old Mithun Koley, who was lying in a coma for almost four months, died in a private hospital in Chennai on Monday night. Koley had been in a coma ever since he was dumped in front of Nilratan Sircar Hospital in the city three days after his abduction on November 10, 2003. Mithun was dumped near the hospital in an unconscious state three days after he was kidnapped from his Dum Dum residence. Later, he was shifted to a private hospital in Chennai where he died, said Manoranjan Saha , additional superintendent of police, Salt Lake. The police said chances of Mithuns survival were becoming increasingly remote as he had developed gangrene near his neck. He was taken to Chennai in a critical condition as the deep gash in his skull had permanently affected his brain, an official said.																																																		Mayor Subrata Mukherjee has ordered municipal commissioner Debashis Som to showcause 10 CMC engineers, associated with CMC Engineers and Allied Services, for running a hotel from the CMC headquarters and various borough offices. Former civic employee and Trinamul Congress MLA Sovandeb Chattopadhyay on Wednesday handed over a printed leaflet publicising a newly constructed holiday home at Peiling run by Talash. The leaflet mentioned the official address of Talash as a room adjacent to the personnel department on the first floor of the CMC headquarters. 																																																		City civic authorities have spent a record Rs 811 crore in the year 2003-2004. Mayor Subrata Mukherjee announced this while placing a deficit interim budget of Rs 7 crore for the first three months for 2004-2005. It is the first time that the CMC had to pass an interim budget because of the new directives from the Election Commission. In the interim budget an expenditure of Rs 192 crore was passed against an estimated earning of Rs 185 crore. 																																																		A man was detained for smuggling on Wednesday at the Netaji Subhash International Airport while trying to board a Singapore-bound flight. He was handed over to the airport police. According to police sources, cash in US and Indian currency, worth nearly Rs 18 lakh, were recovered from him.																																																		An anticipatory bail plea filed by Mohammad Abduz Rabbani, a quack, was rejected on Wednesday by a division bench of Justice D.P. Sengupta and Justice P.K. Deb. According to high court sources, Jahanara Bibi had filed a complaint a few days ago at the Swarupnagar police station, in North 24-Parganas, alleging that Rabbani was responsible for her babys death.																																																		After over a fortnight, the STAR and Sony channels returned to the homes of cable TV viewers, serviced by multi-system-operator (MSO) CableComm early on Wednesday. The impasse between CableComm and RPG Netcom, the city distributor of the two packages, was resolved on Tuesday evening. Though officials of both CableComm and RPG Netcom refused comment on the agreement reached, sources said CableComm has committed to clear all outstanding dues to other MSOs over the next few months. The bouquets had been taken off air on March 10 for a number of reasons, including CableComms alleged outstanding payment to other MSOs and sheltering defaulting operators.																																																		Jugnu Sharma, 28, hanged himself on Wednesday evening at his Mallik Street residence, in Burrabazar. According to police, a quarrel broke out between Sharma, a trader, and his father after he returned home late on Tuesday in an intoxicated state. He left a suicide note.																																																		An unidentified 30-year-old man was lynched at Kalikapur in the East Jadavpur police station area on Wednesday when he was caught while trying to steal a cow. According to police sources, local residents tied him to a roadside post and beat him to death.To Calcutta Municipal Corporations central stores for being recommended for an ISO 9001 certification by British Standard Institution
